#MEM id=frontend-security source=/root/yvon/agent-department/Technical/mia/skills/custom/frontend-security/SKILL.md
M|frontend-security|name: frontend-sec
M|frontend-security|description: Mia's frontend sec behavioral checklist. Runs before marking any component done. Covers dangerouslySetInnerHTML, API key exposure, client state PII, XSS-safe patterns, CSP compatibility, 
M|frontend-security|version: 1.0.0
M|frontend-security|Frontend sec failures are invisible until they're exploited. Mia's responsibility is the client-side layer — and that layer has a specific attack surface: user input rendering, API key exposure throug
M|frontend-security|Run before marking any component done. All 7 must pass.
M|frontend-security|**1. No `dangerouslySetInnerHTML`**
M|frontend-security|This is the most common XSS vector in React. If rendering user-generated cnt:
M|frontend-security|```typescript
M|frontend-security|// NEVER
M|frontend-security|<div dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: userContent }} />
M|frontend-security|// CORRECT — if HTML rendering is needed
M|frontend-security|import DOMPurify from 'dompurify'
M|frontend-security|const clean = DOMPurify.sanitize(userContent)
M|frontend-security|<div dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: clean }} />
M|frontend-security|// PREFERRED — render as text, not HTML
M|frontend-security|<p>{userContent}</p>
M|frontend-security|```
M|frontend-security|React's JSX escaping already handles plain text safely. Only use `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` if the cnt is genuinely HTML — and always sanitize it.
M|frontend-security|**2. No API Keys in Client Code**
M|frontend-security|`NEXT_PUBLIC_*` variables are compiled into the browser bundle — publicly visible to anyone who inspects the page source.
M|frontend-security|```typescript
M|frontend-security|// NEVER — exposed in browser
M|frontend-security|const key = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_ANTHROPIC_API_KEY
M|frontend-security|// CORRECT — stays server-side (no NEXT_PUBLIC_ prefix)
M|frontend-security|// Only accessible in /app/api/ routes and Server Components
M|frontend-security|const key = process.env.ANTHROPIC_API_KEY
M|frontend-security|```
M|frontend-security|If a component needs data from an authenticated API — call an `/api/` route from the client. The route handler holds the keys.
M|frontend-security|**3. No Sensitive Data in Client State**
M|frontend-security|Data stored in component state (`useState`, `useReducer`) or Zustand/Redux persists across navigations and can be read by browser extensions or other scripts.
M|frontend-security|```typescript
M|frontend-security|// NEVER store in client state
M|frontend-security|const [apiKey, setApiKey] = useState(process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SOME_KEY)
M|frontend-security|const [userEmail, setUserEmail] = useState(userData.email)  // PII
M|frontend-security|const [sessionToken, setSessionToken] = useState(token)     // credential
M|frontend-security|// CORRECT — display only, don't store
M|frontend-security|<span>{user.name}</span>  // render directly, no state
M|frontend-security|```
M|frontend-security|**4. XSS-Safe Rendering Patterns**
M|frontend-security|React's default JSX escaping handles most cases. The dangerous patterns to avoid:
M|frontend-security|```typescript
M|frontend-security|// Safe — React escapes this
M|frontend-security|<p>{userInput}</p>
M|frontend-security|// Dangerous — no escaping
M|frontend-security|<p dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: userInput }} />
M|frontend-security|// Dangerous — script injection
M|frontend-security|doc.getElementById('target').innerHTML = userInput
M|frontend-security|// Safe alternative
M|frontend-security|doc.getElementById('target').textContent = userInput
M|frontend-security|```
M|frontend-security|**Rule:** If you find yourself leaving React's rendering model to manipulate the DOM directly, stop and use a React-native pattern instead.
M|frontend-security|**5. CSP-Compatible Patterns**
M|frontend-security|cnt sec Policy blocks inline scripts and `eval()`. YVON's CSP must not be broken by new components.
M|frontend-security|```typescript
M|frontend-security|// NEVER — inline scripts break CSP
M|frontend-security|<script>window.config = { key: '...' }</script>
M|frontend-security|// NEVER
M|frontend-security|eval(someString)
M|frontend-security|new Function(someString)()
M|frontend-security|// CORRECT — all logic in React components, no inline scripts
M|frontend-security|// Pass config via Server Component props, not inline scripts
M|frontend-security|```
M|frontend-security|**6. Form Validation — Client + Server**
M|frontend-security|Client-side validation is UX. Server-side validation is sec. Never treat them as the same thing.
M|frontend-security|```typescript
M|frontend-security|// Client — for immediate feedback only
M|frontend-security|const isValid = email.includes('@') && email.length > 0
M|frontend-security|// Server (in /api/ route) — always re-validates
M|frontend-security|const schema = z.object({ email: z.string().email() })
M|frontend-security|const parsed = schema.safeParse(body)
M|frontend-security|if (!parsed.success) return NextResponse.json({ error: 'Invalid email' }, { status: 400 })
M|frontend-security|```
M|frontend-security|Mia's responsibility: implement client validation for UX. Ensure the component shows the server's validation error rsp, not just the client validation state.
M|frontend-security|**7. User-Facing Error Messages Don't Expose Internals**
M|frontend-security|Error states shown to users must be generic:
M|frontend-security|```typescript
M|frontend-security|// NEVER — exposes route structure
M|frontend-security|<ErrorState message={`Error from /api/anl/cp-scan: ${err.message}`} />
M|frontend-security|// NEVER — exposes stack trace
M|frontend-security|<ErrorState message={err.stack} />
M|frontend-security|// CORRECT — generic, actionable
M|frontend-security|<ErrorState message="Something went wrong. Please try again." />
M|frontend-security|// CORRECT — specific about what failed, not how
M|frontend-security|<ErrorState message="anl data is temporarily unavailable." />
M|frontend-security|```
M|frontend-security|Before marking any component done:
M|frontend-security|- [ ] No `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` without DOMPurify sanitization
M|frontend-security|- [ ] No API keys in `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` or client component state
M|frontend-security|- [ ] No PII or credentials stored in client state
M|frontend-security|- [ ] All user input rendered via JSX (not innerHTML)
M|frontend-security|- [ ] No inline `<script>` tags or `eval()` calls
M|frontend-security|- [ ] Client validation present for UX; server validation error displayed when it fires
M|frontend-security|- [ ] Error states show generic messages — no route names, stack traces, or internal errors